In this work, samples were specifically prepared to investigate the effects of annealing temperature (AT), deposition amount (DA), and dwelling time (DT) on Au NPs on Si (111). For substrates, 4-inch p-type singular-Si (111) with a thickness of 1000Â Î¼m were diced into 1âÃâ1Â cm2 in a dicing saw and treated with the RCA clean. Prior to the deposition of gold, samples were degassed at 850Â Â°C for 30Â min under 1âÃâ10â4Â Torr in a pulsed laser deposition (PLD) system to get rid of surface oxide and other contaminants. Additional file 1: Figure S1 shows the Raman spectra of the bare Si surface excited with a CW diode-pumped solid-state (DPPS) laser of a wavelength of 532âÂ±â1Â nm with an output power of 120Â mW. For the variation of DA, in general, Au was deposited at a rate of 0.05Â nm/s with the ionization current of 3Â mA in a plasma ion-coating chamber under 1âÃâ10â1Â Torr and the ionization time was varied to achieve each DA (0.25, 0.5, 1, 2, 3, 4, 4.5, 5, 5.5, 6, 8, and 16Â nm). After the Au deposition, surface morphologies of samples were relatively smooth, as clearly shown in Additional file 2: Figure S2. For the investigation of the DT effect on Au NPs, samples were systematically annealed at a pre-determined temperature of 700Â Â°C with a fixed DA of 2Â nm for 30Â s up to 5Â h, respectively. Samples were annealed by a halogen lamp at a ramping rate of 2.3Â Â°C/s under a chamber pressure of 1âÃâ10â4Â Torr. The procedure was operated by a computer controlled recipe. In order to investigate the evolution of Au NPs depending on the AT, similarly 2Â nm of Au was equally deposited on the substrate and the samples were annealed with the variation of AT from 50 to 850Â Â°C for a fixed annealing duration of 30Â s. With the termination of each growth recipe, the temperature was quenched immediately to get rid of the Ostwald-ripening [32â34]. Subsequent to the sample synthesis, for the smaller area characterization, the surface morpholo