				\begin{document}$$ {R_{\mathrm{D}}}^4\approx \frac{D_{\mathrm{S}}\gamma {\Omega}^{4/3}}{kT}{D}_{\mathrm{C}} $$\end{document} [29, 30], where DC is the critical DA, Î³ is the surface free energy, the Î© is the atomic volume of Au, k is the Boltzmann constant, T is the absolute temperature, and DS is the diffusion coefficient as a function of T. Given that the AT has been fixed under the increased DA, as soon as the radius of Au NPs reached the <RD>, the coalescence can begin to occur and the wiggly nanostructures can form instead of the round dome-shaped NPs. With further increased DAs, even a layer can be expected to form along with the preferential lateral coalescence. As described, the evolution of Au nanostructures based on the coalescence and V-W growth models in the dimension and configuration is clearly presented in Figs.Â 2 and 3. Initially, the round dome-shaped Au NPs with well-packed density were fabricated with 2Â nm DA in Figs.Â 2a and 3a. With only additional 1Â nm more DA, the dimension of the Au NPs was expanded both laterally and vertically as shown in Figs.Â 2b and 3b. At 4.5Â nm, the vertical size expansion of Au NPs became slower likely due to reaching the <RD>, and the lateral growth became more obvious, which resulted in the presence of elongated Au NPs, as in Figs.Â 2c and 3c. Then, the Au NPs gradually coalesced into wiggly nanostructures along with the increased DAs, as evidenced by the coalescence occurring at 6Â nm in Figs.Â 2d and 3d. As sharply compared in the cross-sectional line profiles in Fig.Â 2(a-1), (d-1), the height of resulting nanostructures were radically increased with the increased DAs from 2 to 6Â nm. The morphological evolution can also be observed with the Fourier filter transform (FFT) power spectra in Fig.Â 2(a-2), (d-2). Initially, at 2Â nm the spectrum covered almost 90Â %, but, with the increased DAs, the spectra gradually shrunk into a small spot due to the reduced frequencies. To specify the DA effect on the siz